2. Visualization, Outliers and Missing Values

## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Observation:

  • Out of 263 data points, block 52 accounts more than twice compares to block B. Accordingly, AQ, KL and CV areas are the top 3 area have the most data points collected.

  • A large majority of data points are collected at shallow depths (i.e.horizons F, H, I)

  • Data source from MLC occupies more than half of the entire data set which is less reliable to assess the fluid property analysis.

  • Netpay distribution is highly skewed to the left. There are outliers which will be analyzed in the next step.

  • Mole fraction of C5+ components are insignificant (i.e.less than 5%)

  • CO2 and N2 are also skewed to the left. Most of the CO2 data points lie between 0 - 20% while there are existing outliers above 40%. N2 are mostlikely between 0-5% while there are outliers above 10.

  • Descriptive statistics (i.e.mean, min, max, Q1 and Q3) are showed previously.

Outliers

Now, look at the boxplot of the key features which seems to have outliers identified from previous histogram:

  • Porosity, Sw and C1 seem to be normally distributed even though C1 has a some minor outliers at the low-end.

  • Netpay, CO2 and GHV have many outliers. In addition, iC5 has several outliers at the high-end. However, we ignore iC5 due to its narrow range and will focus on Netpay and CO2 for further investigation. Most of the GHV data points in this study are formularized from C composition and CO2 (i.e.MLC data source), so it correlates very well with CO2 and compositions. Therefore, we ignore it in outlier analysis but it is considered as a dependent variable (response), so we will relate it in the model training and prediction at a later time.

  • Facet with different categories as the following plots:

CO2:

  • Once facetting in different horizons, CO2 is more normally distributed. The high-end values (i.e. >30%) observed from the previous boxplot without facetting is now allocated to I and J horizons, mostly in AQ area.

  • It turns out that the numbers of outliers of CO2 are reduced to 5 (3 data points in AQ, 1 data point in each CV and KL: AQ-4X, AQ-7X, CV-3X and KL-3X).

  • J Sand only appears in KL, AQ and CV areas and CO2 in AQ is the highest. All CO2 in J sand are relatively normal distribution.

  • CO2 of I formation in AQ area is variated significantly (i.e.from very low value less than 5% to the highest value of more than 50%). This distribution is far different with the remaining and it is very interested to investigate further.

Netpay:

  • Netpay is the most left-skewed distributed among all features and seems to have log-normal distribution with mean values at lower-bound in the boxplot, especially in formation F. Therefore, the following normal boxplot cannot identify the outliers.

  • We transform Netpay to log-normal as the following plot. It turns out that AQ and CV areas exist several outliers in the formation F, H, J and M as indicated in the wellname AQ4X, AQ6X, CV-1X, CV-4X and CV-5X.
